  <p>One of the first questions Melbourne homeowners ask when they think about getting their chimney cleaned is: <strong>how much is this actually going to cost me?</strong> The answer varies more than you'd expect — and not always for good reasons.</p>

  <p>Here's a straightforward breakdown of what chimney sweeping costs in Melbourne in 2026, what you should get for your money, and the warning signs of a quote that's too good to be true.</p>

  <h2>Typical Chimney Sweep Prices in Melbourne</h2>

  <p>For a standard chimney sweep and inspection on a single chimney, Melbourne prices generally fall in the range of <strong>$150 to $320</strong>. The wide spread comes down to a few factors: the type of system you have, the level of buildup, the size of the chimney, and whether the tradie is charging a call-out fee on top.</p>

  <p>At the lower end you'll find operators who may be cutting corners on thoroughness — a quick brush through without a proper inspection isn't really a sweep, it's a token clean. At the higher end you're often paying for a company with high overheads, not necessarily better work.</p>

  <p>Dave's Chimney Sweeping charges <strong>$199 flat</strong> — that covers the full clean and inspection, and there's no call-out fee on top. The same price applies whether you're in Toorak or Sunbury.</p>

  <h2>What Should Be Included in a Chimney Sweep?</h2>

  <p>A proper chimney sweep isn't just sticking a brush up the flue. When you pay for a chimney clean, here's what should be included:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Full chimney sweep from firebox to pot</strong> — brushing and clearing the entire flue, not just the lower section</li>
    <li><strong>Creosote and soot removal</strong> — this is the main reason you're getting it done; creosote is the flammable residue that builds up with wood burning</li>
    <li><strong>Blockage check</strong> — bird nests, debris and collapsed mortar can block airflow</li>
    <li><strong>Condition report</strong> — at minimum a verbal summary of what was found and whether anything needs attention</li>
    <li><strong>Clean-up</strong> — dust sheets should be laid down and all soot and ash contained and removed</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="callout">
    <p>If a quote doesn't mention soot removal or a condition report, ask specifically what's included. Some low-cost operators do a surface clean only and leave the ash and debris behind.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Does the Type of Fireplace Affect the Price?</h2>

  <p>It can. Open fireplaces and closed slow-combustion wood heaters have different chimney configurations, and the level of access and cleaning required can differ. A slow combustion heater with a stainless liner, for instance, takes a bit more time to clean properly than a simple open fireplace.</p>

  <p>Some operators charge extra for wood heaters versus open fireplaces. Dave's $199 rate covers both — wood heaters, slow combustion heaters and open fireplaces are all the same price.</p>

  <h2>What About Call-Out Fees?</h2>

  <p>This is where some quotes get inflated. A tradie might advertise a $140 chimney sweep and then add a $60–$80 call-out fee on top. Always ask whether the quoted price is the total price. The $199 Dave charges is the complete cost — no call-out, no travel surcharge, no add-ons.</p>

  <h2>Multiple Chimneys — Is There a Discount?</h2>

  <p>If you have a larger period home with multiple chimneys — common in Melbourne's inner suburbs like Kew, Hawthorn, Malvern and Brighton — it's worth asking about pricing for multiple flues in a single visit. Having them all done at once saves on scheduling and is usually more economical per chimney than separate visits.</p>

  <h2>Is the Cheapest Quote the Best Option?</h2>

  <p>Not usually. A chimney that hasn't been properly cleaned can cause a chimney fire — which is a house fire. This isn't a job where saving $30 is worth the risk of a rushed or incomplete clean. The question to ask isn't just "how much?" but "what exactly do I get?"</p>

  <p>A reputable local operator who can tell you exactly what they'll do, how long it'll take, and what they found afterwards is worth more than the lowest number on a price comparison site.</p>

  <h2>Is Chimney Sweeping Worth the Cost?</h2>

  <p>Yes — both financially and for safety. The cost of a chimney fire, whether in insurance excess, damage, or emergency services, is orders of magnitude higher than an annual clean. Most Melbourne home insurers also require evidence of regular maintenance for fire-related claims to be valid.</p>

  <p>At $199 a year, chimney sweeping is one of the cheaper maintenance tasks for a home with a wood fire — especially given what it protects against.</p>
